Realtors Lose in Court
----------------------

From the Wall Street Journal ( https://www.wsj.com/real-estate/jury-finds-r=
ealtors-conspired-to-keep-commissions-high-awards-nearly-1-8-billion-in-dam=
ages-b26f9c2f ) :

A federal jury on Tuesday found the National Association of Realtors and la=
rge residential brokerages liable for about $1.8 billion in damages after d=
etermining they conspired to keep commissions for home sales artificially h=
igh. The verdict could lead to industrywide upheaval by changing decades-ol=
d rules that have helped lock in commission rates even as home prices have =
skyrocketed =E2=80=94 which has allowed real-estate agents to collect ever-=
larger sums. It comes in the first of two antitrust lawsuits arguing that u=
nlawful industry practices have left consumers unable to lower their costs =
even though internet-era innovations have allowed many buyers to find homes=
 themselves online=E2=80=A6

This topic was covered in Tuesday=E2=80=99s episode of Sharp Tech ( https:/=
/sharptech.fm/member/episode/the-future-of-buying-and-selling-houses-two-pr=
ice-fixing-lawsuits-the-in-season-tournament-and-ronald-reagan ) , and I th=
ink it=E2=80=99s worth covering here, particularly given I=E2=80=99ve touch=
ed on these issues in the past. To briefly summarize how the industry has w=
orked to date:

* A seller hires a real estate agent to sell their house. The real estate a=
gent will help prep the house, take pictures, and prepare the listing.
* Said listing is placed on what are known as multiple listing services (ML=
Ss), which were originally conceived of as a way to make real estate agents=
 representing buyers aware of what houses were for sale; over time MLSs hav=
e become electronic with APIs, making them accessible to companies like Zil=
low.
* As a prerequisite of making said listing, the seller agent has to specify=
 a commission for the buying agent (to be paid by the seller agent); the st=
andard rate is 6% for the entire transaction, with 3% to the selling and bu=
ying agents respectively.

This entire structure made a lot more sense before the Internet: as I noted=
 the entire reason MLSs were created was to help match sellers with buyers.=
 This, by extension, meant that the value buying agents could provide to se=
llers was not just helping with inspections and titles and contracts, but a=
ctually finding houses in the first place. That value, however, is a lot le=
ss in the context of a platform like Zillow: I was just procrastinating by =
looking at houses while writing this Update, with nary a real estate agent =
in site!

And yet the fees persist, thanks to the essential nature of MLSs, and the a=
ccompanying contractural requirement to keep the current fee structure in p=
lace (the amount of the fee can vary, but not the structure); that requirem=
ent is what was found to be illegal.

