Notice how little power Spotify and Apple Music have; neither has a suffici=
ent user base to attract suppliers (artists) based on pure economics, in pa=
rt because they don=E2=80=99t have access to back catalogs. Unlike newspape=
rs, music labels built an integration that transcends distribution.

Aggregators dominate markets that are commoditized (Google is the ultimate =
example here); the best way to resist an Aggregator is to have some sort of=
 critical integration that prevents commoditization. In this case the real =
estate agent industry had managed to integrate MLS with the 6% commission s=
tructure; unlike the music labels, though, which benefited from the fact th=
at new music releases immediately become back catalog content, the real est=
ate agent integration relied on contractural requirements that a federal co=
urt just decided amounted to collusion.

From Franchises to Businesses
-----------------------------

Again from the Wall Street Journal ( https://www.wsj.com/finance/investing/=
the-way-you-pay-to-buy-or-sell-a-home-is-about-to-change-4e1a4fbc ) :

Home buyers and sellers face the prospect of major changes to the amount an=
d the ways they pay their real-estate agents, following Tuesday=E2=80=99s h=
istoric verdict against the National Association of Realtors and large resi=
dential brokerages. Those changes could range from minor tweaks to the comm=
ission system to a more radical restructuring of the residential real-estat=
e industry, such as more people buying homes without using agents or buyers=
 paying their agents by the hour.

It=E2=80=99s still up in the air what will come of this specific decision; =
if, though, these contractural requirements go away, then I think that Zill=
ow will finally have their opportunity.

Imagine a future where a seller can only ever agree to a selling agent=E2=
=80=99s commission, and that there is no limitation on placing a listing on=
 MLS: in this world buying agents still have some value, particularly given=
 the fact that a home purchase is the largest purchase in most people=E2=80=
=99s lives, and there is an opportunity to help actually seeing houses and =
providing a guiding hand around inspections, mortgages, titles, etc. What I=
 didn=E2=80=99t list is actually finding a home, because the reality is tha=
t most home buyers already do that on their own, mostly on Zillow.

What will be different is that it will be the buyer, not the seller, who is=
 deciding how much the buying agent gets paid. The National Association of =
Realtors argues that this will hurt buyers, because they will have to pay m=
ore, but the reality is they were paying anyways =E2=80=94 they just had no=
 say in how much, or for what services. Now real estate agents on the buyin=
g side will have to price in a way that reflects the reality that most buye=
rs find their own houses, and I suspect that price will be a lot less.

The answer from the more enterprising real estate agents should be to make =
it up in volume: if you don=E2=80=99t actually do that much for buyers, at =
least compared to the pre-Internet era, then sure, perhaps you can=E2=80=99=
t charge as much. However, you can also do a lot more deals, assuming, of c=
ourse, you can acquire the customers. And how do you acquire customers at s=
cale? Well, it turns out there is already a customer acquisition platform p=
erfectly positioned at the point where customers begin their search: Zillow=
.

This will, I should note, be a difficult transition for realtors: as long a=
s you closed just a handful of deals a year than you could earn a very reas=
onable salary; now you will have to work much harder to earn an equivalent =
amount, and I suspect a lot of agents will end up exiting the industry. Wha=
t is interesting is that one of the biggest players on the brokerage side i=
s Warren Buffett, and I can imagine he=E2=80=99s not too thrilled about the=
 outcome. He once explained why he was leaving the newspaper industry in th=
e 1992 Berkshire Hathaway letter to shareholders ( http://www.berkshirehath=
away.com/letters/1991.html ) :

The fact is that newspaper, television, and magazine properties have begun =
to resemble businesses more than franchises in their economic behavior=E2=
=80=A6An economic franchise arises from a product or service that: (1) is n=
eeded or desired; (2) is thought by its customers to have no close substitu=
te and; (3) is not subject to price regulation. The existence of all three =
conditions will be demonstrated by a company=E2=80=99s ability to regularly=
 price its product or service aggressively and thereby to earn high rates o=
f return on capital. Moreover, franchises can tolerate mis-management. Inep=
t managers may diminish a franchise=E2=80=99s profitability, but they canno=
t inflict mortal damage.

In contrast, =E2=80=9Ca business=E2=80=9D earns exceptional profits only if=
 it is the low-cost operator or if supply of its product or service is tigh=
t. Tightness in supply usually does not last long. With superior management=
, a company may maintain its status as a low-cost operator for a much longe=
r time, but even then unceasingly faces the possibility of competitive atta=
ck. And a business, unlike a franchise, can be killed by poor management.

Until recently, media properties possessed the three characteristics of a f=
ranchise and consequently could both price aggressively and be managed loos=
ely. Now, however, consumers looking for information and entertainment (the=
ir primary interest being the latter) enjoy greatly broadened choices as to=
 where to find them. Unfortunately, demand can=E2=80=99t expand in response=
 to this new supply: 500 million American eyeballs and a 24-hour day are al=
l that=E2=80=99s available. The result is that competition has intensified,=
 markets have fragmented, and the media industry has lost some =E2=80=94 th=
ough far from all =E2=80=94 of its franchise strength.

Before this decision, the real estate business was a franchise; going forwa=
rd, assuming this decision leads to the sort of changes I expect, it is goi=
ng to be a business. That=E2=80=99s good for consumers, and it=E2=80=99s go=
od for Zillow, which, I will add, is not a surprise: remember that Aggregat=
ors derive their power from marshaling demand because they offer a product =
that consumers want. It follows that what is good for the Aggregator is goo=
d for consumers, and vice-versa; it=E2=80=99s the folks in the middle that =
get squeezed, whether that be publishers, TV studios, or, in this case, rea=
ltors.

